  "content": "# HACCP Plan for Food Safety - Enhanced Workflow Prompt\n\nYou are tasked with drafting a comprehensive Hazard Analysis and Critical Control Points (HACCP) Plan for a food safety regulatory document. This plan must comply with FDA and USDA requirements and serve as a legally defensible framework for identifying, monitoring, and controlling food safety hazards throughout the production process.\n\n## Context and Approach\n\nBegin by gathering all relevant information about the client's food production operations. Search the user's uploaded documents for existing process flows, facility layouts, product specifications, and any prior safety documentation. This will provide the foundation for a customized HACCP plan rather than a generic template. Supplement this document-specific information with current regulatory guidance from FDA and USDA official sources to ensure the plan meets all federal compliance standards.\n\nThe HACCP plan you create must be both scientifically sound and legally compliant. Each section should reference authoritative sources including FDA regulations (21 CFR Part 117 for preventive controls, 21 CFR Part 123 for seafood, 9 CFR Part 417 for meat and poultry), USDA guidelines, and recognized industry standards. When citing regulatory requirements, verify that you are referencing the current, enforceable versions of these regulations.\n\n## Document Structure and Content Requirements\n\n**Preliminary Information Section**: Draft a comprehensive introduction that identifies the food business entity with complete legal name, address, and contact information. Describe each product covered by the plan including ingredients, processing methods, packaging, storage conditions, shelf life, and intended use and consumers. Include the distribution methods and geographic scope. Search official FDA and USDA resources for model HACCP plan templates specific to the product category, and cite the relevant guidance documents that inform this section's structure.\n\n**Hazard Analysis Section**: Conduct a thorough hazard analysis by examining each step in the production process from receiving raw materials through distribution. Review any uploaded process flow diagrams or operational documents to identify where biological hazards (pathogens, toxins), chemical hazards (allergens, cleaning agents, pesticides), and physical hazards (metal, glass, plastic) may be introduced, increased, or controlled. For each identified hazard, assess the likelihood of occurrence and severity of health consequences. Reference FDA's HACCP principles and USDA's hazard analysis guidance, citing specific sections that address hazard identification methodologies. The analysis must demonstrate a systematic evaluation of each process step.\n\n**Critical Control Points Section**: Identify and justify each Critical Control Point in the process using the CCP decision tree methodology. A CCP is a step where control can be applied and is essential to prevent, eliminate, or reduce a food safety hazard to acceptable levels. Distinguish CCPs from control points that manage quality but not safety. Search USDA guidebooks and FDA compliance resources for industry-specific best practices in CCP identification, particularly for the product type in question. Document the scientific or regulatory basis for designating each CCP, and explain why control at this point is critical to food safety.\n\n**Critical Limits Section**: For each identified CCP, establish specific, measurable critical limits that separate acceptable from unacceptable conditions. These limits must be based on scientific literature, regulatory standards, or experimental studies. Common critical limits include time and temperature parameters, pH levels, water activity, preservative concentrations, or physical dimensions. Search FDA regulations and food safety codes for legally mandated critical limits applicable to the specific hazards and products. Cite the regulatory authority or scientific source for each critical limit, ensuring that the limits are more stringent than or equal to regulatory minimums. Include the rationale for selecting each limit and explain how it controls the identified hazard.\n\n**Monitoring Procedures Section**: Describe detailed monitoring procedures for each CCP that specify what will be monitored, how monitoring will be conducted, the frequency of monitoring, and who is responsible for monitoring. Monitoring must be continuous or at a frequency sufficient to ensure the CCP remains under control. Include the specific instruments or methods used for measurement, calibration requirements, and the qualifications of personnel conducting monitoring. Search food safety authority resources and industry templates for monitoring best practices, ensuring procedures are practical for the operational environment while maintaining scientific validity. Document how monitoring records will be reviewed and by whom.\n\n**Corrective Actions Section**: Outline predetermined corrective action procedures for each CCP that will be implemented when monitoring indicates a deviation from a critical limit. Corrective actions must address both the immediate control of the affected product and the correction of the process to prevent recurrence. Review any business-specific risk factors in uploaded documents that might inform corrective action protocols. Specify who has authority to initiate corrective actions, how affected product will be identified and segregated, the evaluation process for product disposition, and the steps to restore process control. Search official FDA and USDA resources for corrective action frameworks and cite relevant regulatory requirements for corrective action documentation.\n\n**Verification and Validation Section**: Detail comprehensive verification procedures to confirm that the HACCP plan is working as intended. Verification activities should include calibration of monitoring equipment, review of CCP monitoring records, review of corrective action records, visual inspections, and periodic testing or sampling. Establish the frequency for each verification activity and assign responsibility. Include validation procedures that provide scientific or technical evidence that the HACCP plan, when properly implemented, will effectively control the identified hazards. Cite FDA and USDA verification guidelines, and reference any industry-specific validation studies or regulatory guidance. Address how the plan will be reassessed when changes occur in raw materials, product formulation, processing methods, or when new hazards are identified.\n\n**Record-Keeping and Documentation Section**: Specify all records that must be maintained to document the HACCP system, including the hazard analysis, CCP monitoring records, critical limit deviation records, corrective action records, and verification and validation records. For each record type, indicate the information to be captured, the format, the retention period, and the storage location. Search official legal and regulatory sources for HACCP record-keeping requirements, noting that FDA regulations typically require records to be maintained for at least two years or the shelf life of the product, whichever is longer. Cite specific regulatory sections that mandate record retention periods. Address how records will be made available for regulatory inspection and how confidentiality of proprietary information will be maintained.\n\n## Final Document Assembly\n\nOnce you have gathered all necessary regulatory citations, reviewed relevant uploaded documents for business-specific details, and researched current FDA and USDA guidance for each section, create a comprehensive HACCP Plan document. The document should be professionally formatted with clear section headings, numbered subsections for each CCP, and properly cited references to all regulatory and scientific sources. Include a signature page for the HACCP team members and management approval. The final plan must be both a practical operational tool for the food business and a legally compliant regulatory document that demonstrates due diligence in food safety management.\n\nEnsure that every assertion about regulatory requirements is supported by citation to the specific regulation or guidance document, and that all critical limits and monitoring procedures are scientifically justified and practically implementable for the client's specific operations.",
